    <h3 class="title"><a href="/battlestar/battlestars-daybreak-worst-ending-history-screen-science-fiction#comment-10092" class="active">Interesting essay</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="http://colinprincipe.com" rel="nofollow">Colin Principe</a> (not verified) on Thu, 2009-07-16 12:51.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>This is extremely well thought-out and constructed, and serves as a wonderful glossary on the goals of science fiction and its methods.</p>
<p>I would propose one thought about why religion / "God's plan" plays so prominently in BSG: I believe that good SF speaks to things that are occurring in the time in which is is written.  Hence "Star Trek" explored issues of race, as did "Planet of the Apes;" "Star Trek: The Next Generation" explored gender issues.  BSG had a lot of examinations of current events: terrorism and the 'war on terror;' the 'enemy among us' concept; what is the line between winning a war and losing one's humanity.  Up until recently, the intertwining of religion and politics in the USA became stronger than ever - and BSG's exploration of religion / "God's plan" may be because of this fact.</p>
<p>Doesn't excuse the ending though, I was disappointed too.</p>
